15 August 2025

DBSV Sales Note

[cid:image002.jpg@01DC0DCC.EFCA8A30]


TOP IDEA
JD.com: Food delivery hits near-term profits but boosts cross-selling
[cid:image003.png@01DC0DCC.EFCA8A30]<https://www.dbs.com/insightsdirect/company/TR5041064571?source=landing&pagesec=whatsnew&pagesecid=27328>


  *   2Q25 non-GAAP net profit declined by 49% y/y to RMB7.4bn, but was 24% above market expectations, due to higher-than-expected other income and investment gain from investees


  *   Revenue grew by 22.4% y/y to RMB357bn, 6% ahead, driven by better-than-expected 618 performance and stronger food delivery revenue, yet non-GAAP operating profit, reflecting the underlying business growth, recorded RMB896mn (-92% y/y), missing consensus' RMB3.6bn estimates, due to a 128% y/y surge in marketing expense to RMB27.0bn caused by food delivery expansion



  *   Expect JD Retail to continue outperform peers on stronger operational capabilities; Food Delivery to continue bring earnings pressure in 3Q25, while algorithms and system tool launch will further enhance cross-selling efficiency. Maintain BUY on JD for its higher-than-industry revenue growth and undemanding valuation, TP of HKD164/USD42.

What we think: JD.com (9618 HK/JD US) announced its 2Q25 results on August 14, 2025, after the HK market close. Revenue grew 22.4% y/y to RMB356.7bn, 6% ahead of consensus estimates. Net product revenue grew 20.7% y/y to RMB282bn, with strong 23.4% y/y increase in electronics and home appliances revenue, while general merchandise revenue was up 16.4%. This was backed by the strong 618 season and trade-in initiatives. New Business revenue surged c.200% y/y to RMB13.9bn (much higher than estimates' RMB6.8bn), fueled by the expansion of JD Food Delivery business. However, the massive expansion in Food Delivery has caused operating loss in the new business segment widened significantly to RMB14.8bn (vs consensus estimates' RMB8.1bn). JD's non-GAAP net profit decreased by 49% y/y to RMB7.4bn in 2Q25, 24% ahead of consensus estimates.

Given 3Q25 is a Food Delivery high season with JD recording peak order volume in July, we expect fierce competition and heavy marketing spending to weigh on group profitability in 3Q25. We believe the launch of cross-selling using algorithms and systems in 3Q25, will further improve the conversion rate (percentage of food delivery users who also become JD retail users) from around 40% in June. Meanwhile, JD continues to return value to shareholders, buying back USD1.5bn worth of shares in 1H25 (c. 2.8% of shares outstanding as of end-FY24) under its current USD5bn buyback program. The stock is currently trading at 9x 12-month forward P/E, c.1 SD below its historical average. We maintain a BUY rating for JD on its solid core business momentum and undemanding valuation, TP of HKD164/USD42.

CONSUMER
First Resources: Stellar performance in 2Q25
[cid:image003.png@01DC0DCC.EFCA8A30]<https://www.dbs.com/insightsdirect/api/s3/dbs-buffer/article_attachment/20250814/FR14Aug2025.pdf>


  *   2Q25 was ahead of our and consensus estimates, supported by positive impact from the ANJT acquisition


  *   Announced interim dividend of 4.5 SCts/share (36% dividend payout) (1H24: 3.5 Scts/shr)


  *   Maintain BUY with TP of S$2


What we think: 1H25 earnings came in at USD152m (+67.8% y/y), forming 87%/70% of DBS/consensus FY25F earnings estimates of USD200m (-5% y/y)/USD244m (flat y/y). The ANJT acquisition has proven to be positive for FR, delivering a quick and tangible impact - a testament to the management team's strong execution. CPO production rose to 510k MT (+18.6% y/y) in 1H25 while total harvested fresh fruit bunches (FFB) reached 2.0m MT (+23% y/y) in 2Q25. Overall productivity metrics improved, with FFB yield rising to 9.6 MT/ha (+14.3% y/y) and a relatively stable extraction rate of 21.7% versus 1H24's 22.3%.

Given the smooth integration with ANJT, coupled with a positive CPO price outlook in 2H25, we believe FR could sustain its earnings momentum into the second half of the year. We see upside risk to our forecasts if FR maintains this smooth transition into 2H25. We maintain our BUY rating with a TP of SGD2.00, which implies an FY26F PE of 12.7x, or +2 SD above its historical PE multiple. We believe FR deserves a valuation re-rating post-acquisition, supported by a strong CPO price trend in 2H25.




INDUSTRIALS
Airports of Thailand: Speculation on PSC raise priced in
[cid:image003.png@01DC0DCC.EFCA8A30]<https://researchwise.dbsvresearch.com/ResearchManager/DownloadResearch.aspx?E=ighdbkhaf>


  *   Downgrade from HOLD to FULLY VALUED considering AOT's rich valuation with limited earnings growth


  *   3QFY25F core profit soft after weaker tourist numbers and duty-free area reclamation in 2024


  *   Potential PSC hike priced in after recent share price rally; Downgrade to Fully Valued with higher TP of THB32


What we think:  AOT 3QFY25 core profit came in at THB3.72bn (-15% y/y, -24% q/q) - in line with market expectations.  We see AOT moving into the low season in 4QFY25F. In July 2025, inbound tourism continued to contract 16% y/y; we expect slow recovery throughout the quarter. The seasonality impact should see revenue drop both y/y and q/q. Y/y, the company will also face the impact of duty-free area reclamation after inbound duty free ceased operations. Overall, earnings in 4Q25F should be the softest in FY25F.

The recent rally in share price has pushed AOT's FY26 PE multiple to 32.3x. We believe the current valuation has already priced in the potential PSC increase of around THB100 (as reported by local media), leaving limited short- to medium-term upside. For Nantika's DCF-based valuation, she has rolled forward her estimates to FY26F and adopted a more optimistic terminal growth rate of 2.0%, up from 1.5% previously. As a result, our TP has increased from THB28.00 to THB32.00, suggesting 17% downside from current level.

email.subject: Pony.ai, Inc. (PONY US Equity) Company Update Group Conference Call
email.body:
Summary:

At this juncture, China's best robotaxi player (in terms of the algo /
model). Aims to be gross margin break even on robotaxi operations by end
2025 or (if delayed) 1Q26e. Call fleshes out some details behind the current
advancements in robotaxi tech. More for read through on China's robotaxi and
LIDAR industry.

 

IPO 27 Nov 2024 at $13/ ADR. At $17.095 / share, market cap is at US$5.96bn
& EV is US$6.92b. 2024E revenue US$74.67m and PATMI of -145m. 

 

FY24e EV/Sales of 92.7x.

 

Business Description:

Founded in 2016, in Silicon Valley, Pony.ai has quickly become a global
leader in autonomous mobility and is a pioneer in extending autonomous
mobility technologies and services at a rapidly expanding footprint of sites
around the world. Operating Robotaxi, Robotruck and Personally Owned Vehicle
(POV) business units, Pony.ai is an industry leader in the commercialisation
of autonomous driving. In 2022, Pony.ai became the first autonomous company
to receive a licence to operate its self-driving taxis in China.

 

Company Update Group Conference Call

George Shao (Senior Director - Financing, Investment and Strategy)

 

Gross margin positive on robotaxi operation by the end of 2025. If we can
breakeven on robotaxi operation, not on licensing or robotruck etc. If we
can do this right in Tier 1 cities, we can duplicate in other cities. To hit
50 - 100k fleet size, there will be a need to be heavily reliant on renting
cars (to be asset light) and running them as robotaxis. His calculations is
at a fleet size of 30-50k Pony.ai's robotaxis in tier 1 cities, they can
reach group level profitability at the net income or free cash flow level.
Pony.ai plans to run 600 robotaxis by end of 2025 vs 100 in 2024.

 

"Robotaxi operation will enable us to maximise the max revenue and profits
we will get - not by selling the software / hardware. ADAS don't make money
here or anywhere in the world. Any software L2 is L3 in my mind - they both
require a driver. People don't pay anything to OEM for subscription based
model so OEM don't pay a lot to tier 1 software companies. In China, tier 1
software companies cannot make money. 

 

If you charge people for mileage, carry passenger, then you can make money.
We are laser focused on 1 thing right - robotaxi operation, making money by
mileage. We are focused on tier 1 cities."

 

License to operate Robotaxis in Tier 1 cities: 

 

Plans to mass produce with Beijing auto and Guangzhou auto in 2025 - vehicle
coming down from production line in June 2025. After which, it takes 2
months to get the license as this is their 7th generation robotaxis before
taking passengers in September. Their 5/6th generation ones are already
licensed previously. 

 

Pony.ai is the only driverless player in China to get the licenses from all
tier 1 cities. Weride & Baidu are not able to do so. You can only get the
permit if you prove that your safety / speed on the road is adequate amongst
many other things. Weride & Baidu robotaxis drives slowly and blocks traffic
+ their AI isn't as good compared to us. Their autonomous driving is by
remotely driving the vehicle instead of remotely assisting the vehicle (they
have an operator behind a steering wheel whereas Pony's operators use a
mouse to choose how to rectify issues and the car will reverse etc and
decide how much to turn, how far back to reverse on its own). Our operator
only sees 12 screens, he will see if there's any input needed, he can even
deny assisting the vehicle. No one is holding a steering wheel.

 



He was mentioning about this picture where PM Lee visited WeRide where
there's operators behind steering wheels.

 

L2/L3 vs L4

Dr Tiancheng Lou (CTO and Co-founder Pony.ai) has done a lot of interviews
with Chinese reporters. In summary, the better you do on L2/L3, the further
away you are from L4. BYD, Nio, XPeng etc the L2/L3 companies, their
methodology is to learn from human data, to sell as many cars as possible
and learn from them. You can develop very quickly by learning from human
approach but there is an upper limit to it where you can't surpass the human
being in terms of safety etc. Pony.ai realized this 5/6 years ago and they
don't learn form humans, but instead via practice. Reinforced learning
instead of imitation learning. Pony.ai establishes the work model by
themselves, to train and drive itself. "If you don't surpass human, you
can't run robotaxi".

 

"Deepseek of autonomous driving"

Pony.ai uses less powerful chips to do better things. Compared to waymo, we
use L2 kinda chips to do L4 things. Google waymo still uses 2 H100 chips in
the trunk of their vehicle (super expensive, a lot of computing power).
Pony.ai uses NVIDIA Orin-X chips (40/50 times cheaper than the H100s) as our
algo is better than theirs. Even for LIDAR, we can use L2 lidars to do L4.
For L4 lidars, the point cloud is much denser, quality much higher, distance
longer than L2 lidars. A L4 lidar by waymo is >$10k each. The lidar that
Pony.ai uses are the auto grade lidar (the same as Li Auto or Xpeng etc),
its Hesai AT128s, 2-3k rmb each. Waymo has 1 collusion every 30/40k miles,
Pony.ai is 150k miles. Waymo burns 2.5-3bn usd a year, Pony.ai burns 100m
usd a year. A lot of investors say we are the deepseek of autonomous
driving, using way less complicated hardware to accomplish a lot more. 

 

Cost per robotaxi / density of taxis

Today, our mass produced vehicle, lidar chips sensors plus car, is 280k rmb
/ car. This is 7x lower than waymo. Say if we can get 10s of thousands of
vehicles, we can lower that price by a third, which translates to lower
depreciation or rent on the vehicle. We are doing robotaxi operation, each
vehicle revenue depends on density of the robotaxi that you deploy in a
city. The average didi driver in China if he is a full time driver in a Tier
1 city who drives 14-16 hours a day, he can get 30 orders a day or more.
Today pony gets 10-20 a day (in the same Tier 1 cities). The China national
average is 10/15 level. 

 

Market need for taxis

Every 10k people in tier 1 cities needs 400 ride hailing cars. Regardless of
robotaxi or didi. This means that every 2 million population needs 80k ride
hailing cars. Every district in a Tier 1 city has 2m people, each city has
at least 10 districts. (He is implying that each of the Tier 1 city requires
800k ride hailing cars for a total of maybe 3+m vehicles amongst the 4 Tier
1 cities).
